1. Chain convergence check is broken: the code includes '[dead end]' in the chain
   word sets, so every pair of chains that dead-ends reports a false convergence at
   '{[dead end]}'. Fix by either (a) not appending '[dead end]' to the chain list,
   or (b) excluding it from the convergence set comparison.
   File: week05_lotuseaters.py, lines 197-199 (appending) and 222-224 (checking).

2. Substitution chains are very short (2-3 steps for most words, max 6 for 'flower')
   compared to the exercise target of ~10 steps. The greedy strategy of taking the
   first unvisited lemma from the first synset is too conservative. Consider:
   (a) iterating through ALL synsets equally, not just the first;
   (b) ranking candidates by similarity to the original start word;
   (c) allowing multi-word lemma names (currently they are allowed but rarely found).

3. Exercise 1 does not print the number of synsets per thematic word, which is one
   of the metrics the exercise prompt asks for ("Synsets per thematic word: ~5-15").
   The data is computed (hypernym_data[word]['num_synsets']) but never printed.

4. The 'languid' hypernym path has depth 1 because its first synset is a satellite
   adjective (dreamy.s.02), which has no hypernym tree in WordNet. Consider using
   a noun or verb synset if available, or noting that adjectives lack hypernym
   hierarchies and excluding them from the convergence analysis. Currently 'languid'
   silently drops out of all LCS comparisons (it is never in hypernym_data because
   it IS in hypernym_data but its depth-1 path makes LCS results trivial).

5. Exercise 2 only uses the first synset for each word in every pair. For words with
   many senses, a more thorough approach would compute max similarity across all
   synset pairs (the standard practice in WSD literature). This would give a fairer
   picture of how close the words CAN be, not just how close their most frequent
   senses are.

6. No visualization is produced for Exercise 1. The exercise prompt and rubric call
   for a "hypernym tree visualization showing path structure." The script imports
   matplotlib but never uses it. Consider adding a tree diagram or at least an
   ASCII/text tree showing hypernym paths converging.
